'''Evington Bernard Jackson II''' (born May 10, 1980 in [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]]) is an [[Arena football]] [[Fullback (American football)|Fullback]] / [[Linebacker]] for the [[Kentucky Horsemen]] of [[af2]]. He was originally signed by the [[Washington Redskins]] of the [[National Football League]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]].

In his career, Jackson has also played for the [[Louisville Fire]].

==High school career==
Jackson attended [[St. Xavier High School (Louisville)|St. Xavier High School]] where he was a three-year starter at [[Defensive end]] in [[High school football|football]], as well as a [[Center (basketball)|Center]] in [[basketball]]. In football, he was a two-time 4A All-State selection, as well as an All-Region and All-District selection. He also helped lead his team to two state championships in three seasons, with records of 14-1, 10-2 and 12-3, respectively. As a [[Eleventh grade|junior]], he recorded 120 [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]], seven [[Quarterback sack|sacks]], 19 tackles-for-loses, seven forced [[fumble]]s and five tipped passes that resulted in interceptions. As a [[Twelfth grade|senior]], he recorded 119 tackles, and seven sacks. In football, he was a ''[[Parade Magazine|Parade]]'', ''Blue Chip Illustrated'', ''National Recruiting Advisor'', and ''PrepStart All-America'' selection. He also won state titles in [[Discus throw|discus]] and [[Shot put]].

==College career==
Jackson attended [[University of Tennessee|Tennessee]], where in [[1998 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1998]], his freshman season, the Volunteers won the [[NCAA Division I FBS National Football Championship|national championship]].

As a freshman in 1998, Jackson played in 12 games, and was one of five true freshmen to play that season. He was a member of the [[Special teams]] and also played as reserve Defensive end. He recorded seven tackles with two quarterback pressures, a sack and a pass broken up. As a sophomore in [[1999 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1999]], he played in 12 games, and earned his first career start. He was a member of the Special teams who also played at Defensive end. For the season, he he played in every game, including the [[2000 Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta Bowl]], only missed three quarters. For the season, he recorded 19 tackles, a sack, a tackle-for-loss and a pass broken up. In [[2000 NCAA Division I-A football season|2000]] as a junior, he was primarily a Defensive end, who also played Special teams, and he played in 12 games and started two. In the preseason, he was projected to be a starter, but was a backup to starter DeAngelo Lloyd at Left end, until Lloyd suffered a [[head]] injury against [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], which forced Jackson to start against [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]. For the season, he recorded 12 tackles, including four tackles-for-losses, two recovered fumbles and five quarterback hurries. He earned his second start of the season in the [[2001 Cotton Bowl|Cotton Bowl]], a game in which he recorded five tackles, including two for losses. As a senior in [[2001 NCAA Division I-A football season|2001]], he played in 11 games, starting 10, missing one due to suspension for a violation of team rules. Prior to the regular season games against LSU, Jackson worked his way into the [[Starting lineup|starting]] Left end position. His best game of the season came against [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]], in which he recorded eight tackles. For his career, he recorded 78 tackles, three fumble recoveries, five sacks and 10 tackles-for-losses.

==Professional career==
===National Football League===
Jackson went unselected in the [[2002 NFL Draft]], however on April 25, he was signed by the [[Washington Redskins]] as a [[Undrafted free agent|rookie free agent]].<ref name="Skins">{{cite web |url=http://www.kffl.com/player/7244/NFL |title=Bernard Jackson, DL, Free Agent -Redskins | Undrafted Rookie Free Agents Added |work=KFFL.com |date=[[April 25]], [[2002]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref> However, on September 1, he was released in the teams final cuts.<ref name="ESPN">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/teams/transactions?team=was&year=2002 |title=Washington Redskins Transactions - 2002 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref><ref name="Skins" /> But he was signed the next day to the teams' [[practice squad]].<ref name="ESPN" /><ref name="Skins" /> Then, On November 19, he was promoted to the team's active roster<ref>{{cite web |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9803EED81E30F93AA25752C1A9649C8B63 |title=Transactions - Football - National Football League |date=[[November 19]], [[2002]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref><ref name="Skins" /> and played in four games and recorded two tackles. However, on September 1, 2003, he was released again during the teams final cuts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/teams/transactions?team=was&year=2003 |title=Washington Redskins Transactions - 2003 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref> after being sidelined for three weeks with a high [[ankle]] sprain.<ref name="Skins" />

===af2===
In [[2008 af2 season|2008]], after being out of football for four years, Jackson joined [[af2]], a professional [[Arena football]] league. He was assigned to the [[Kentucky Horsemen|Lexington Horsemen]]. On April 10, he was placed on the "Refused to Report" list by the Horsemen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.af2.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=21044&SPID=1710&DB_OEM_ID=3525&ATCLID=1409089 |title=Transactions Bulletin #105 |work=af2.com |publisher=[[af2]] |date=[[May 10]], [[2008]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref> Then on May 5, he was [[Trade (sports)|trade]]d to the [[Louisville Fire]] for Future Considerations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.af2.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=21044&SPID=1710&DB_OEM_ID=3525&ATCLID=1456709 |title=Transactions Bulletin #151 |work=af2.com |publisher=[[af2]] |date=[[May 2]], [[2008]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref> As a rookie in af2, he played in nine games, starting eight. He recorded 19.5 [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]], 4.5 [[Quarterback sack|sacks]], six tackles-for-losses, eight Quarterback hurries, one forced [[fumble]] and three blocked [[Field goal (American football)|kicks]].<ref name="2008 StatGuys">{{cite web |url=http://www.thestatguys.com/AF2/2008/LOU.HTM#igbg.def |title=AF2 - 2008 Season Louisville Fire |work=TheStatGuys.com |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref> He even returned one kickoff for six yards.<ref name="2008 StatGuys" /> On November 1, he was placed on Re-Assignment,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.af2.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=1617819&DB_OEM_ID=3525 |title=Transactions Bulletin #22 - Part 2 |work=af2.com |publisher=[[af2]] |date=[[November 1]], [[2008]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref> which means that the league would assign him to another team. On January 22, 2009 he was re-assigned to the Horsemen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.af2.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=21044&SPID=1710&DB_OEM_ID=3525&ATCLID=3651456 |title=Transactions Bulletin #67 |work=af2.com |publisher=[[af2]] |date=[[January 22]], [[2009]] |accessdate=[[January 25]], [[2009]]}}</ref>

